text: Is this taping now? The tape is now on. Anything you say now will be recorded. Mr. Simak, could you give us your background, where you grew up, how you spent your time as a young boy? I was born on my grandfather's farm, which stood on the high hills above the confluence of the Mississippi and Wisconsin River. And I grew up as a farm boy. I went to a rural high school. We lived and went about to the tail end of the pioneer period. Most of us are. My family is poor, and all of our neighbors were poor. We didn't think we were poor, but we were. We didn't think so because everybody was in the same shape. And I did go to, after high school, I attended the teacher's training course and taught school for a short time. And then went to the University of Wisconsin at Madison, but I did not finish there. I ran out of money. I got a job in the newspaper, and I've been in the newspaper business ever since until six, seven years ago. Seven years ago. Okay. How did you decide to become a newspaper man? I think there was no decision because I think I always knew what I wanted to write. And I never really thought of writing fiction or writing books or anything of that sort. It seemed to me that the way to write was to be a newspaper man. My mother, who was a very well-educated woman, had books in the house all the time, and I read them. And she used to sit at the table by the light of a kerosene lamp and read it each evening after all the work was done. And I asked her at one time, I remember, if a newspaper carried all the news, printed all the news that was. And she, in the manner of that day, and because people were not as cynical then as they are now, said, yes, that's true. And I asked her another question that I thought was important. I said, is all the news true? Is what the newspaper writes true? And again, with that lack of cynicism and faith that the people of that time had, she said, yes, it was. And that decided me, decided me to be, want to be a newspaper man. How long were you in the newspaper business before you wrote your first science fiction stories? No, wait, that's going to take some. I started my newspaper career in 1929. And my first short story appeared in, I think, 1931. And I wrote, at that time I wrote several other short stories which were published. And at about that time the magazine, all magazines, the science fiction magazines and all others, ran into hard times because the Great Depression came along. And so I, there was no market, practically no market. So I dropped out and didn't do any more writing, any other fiction writing of any kind until I think it was 37 or 38. And I started writing again because the magazines had come back. John Camel had been named editor of Astounding. And I felt very sure that I could sell my work to John Camel. So I started in again. And I think since, since 1938, 1939, I think it's 38, 37 or 38. There was only one year in which none of my work appeared. There was one year that's blank. And I can't remember which year that it was. And I have no idea why that occurred. When you began writing fiction, what influenced you to write science fiction? Well, because when I was a boy, I had read, Julius Byrne and, and I think H.G. Wells, although I don't actually remember any H.G. Wells works, but I must have read them. I've read them, like Edgar Allan Poe and Haggard. And I thought what a wonderful thing that was. I just had an awful interest in the field. I wanted to read it myself and I found out when I decided that I wanted to write. When I found out the newspaper didn't give me everything that I wanted in the writing field. I decided that on the part that on my spare time I write, I naturally seemed to turn to science fiction. Because it was something I was acquainted with. I felt very sure that I could do the job of it. And I was quite fortunate, of course, because there was no competition at that time. If you could string three sentences together and make a paragraph, somebody would buy the story. Did you have any interest in science when you were growing up? Some interest. You must realize that at that time, science was a somewhat different thing than it is today. Today, science is something that a good many people are interested in. There are a great many engineers and a great many technicians and just ordinary lay people who are interested in science. At that time, science was a rather elevated situation, elevated crap. There were a few great scientists. There were a few engineers. But mostly those were either mining engineers or civil engineers. There have been very old science, very old pride at that time. And the public interest in it was fairly low. I was taken by them. I used to read, I forget what old magazine it was. It was a magazine. Would it be Scientific American? Would it go back that far? I think so. I used to read Scientific American, which had some marvelous articles in it, particularly on astronomy. I didn't understand any of it, or understood very little of it. But the mystery and the wonder of it caught me by the smoke. And that was the sort of interest I had at that time in it. I don't think very many people had interest in science the way that they can be said to have interest in science today. You mentioned when you resumed your writing in 1938 when the magazines had recovered that you thought you could write for John Campbell. What was in your writing that you thought would appeal to Campbell? I've read a lot of John Campbell's work. I knew that John Campbell was favored what we today call hard science fiction. And I thought that I could write that kind of science fiction. I did write what amounted to hard science fiction for some years, and then began to turn over to the softer science fiction such as most of which... Well, most people write soft science fiction today. Only a few of the old hands and maybe a few new beginners write the hard science fiction today. Some people feel that John Campbell influenced science fiction positively. Others feel that he influenced it very negatively. What's your assessment of his influence on the field? segments.text: Anything you say now will be recorded.
Mr. Simak, could you give us your background, where you grew up, how you spent your time
I was born on my grandfather's farm, which stood on the high hills above the confluence
of the Mississippi and Wisconsin River.
And I grew up as a farm boy.
I went to a rural high school.
We lived and went about to the tail end of the pioneer period.
My family is poor, and all of our neighbors were poor.
We didn't think we were poor, but we were.
We didn't think so because everybody was in the same shape.
And I did go to, after high school, I attended the teacher's training course and taught school
And then went to the University of Wisconsin at Madison, but I did not finish there.
I got a job in the newspaper, and I've been in the newspaper business ever since until six,
How did you decide to become a newspaper man?
I think there was no decision because I think I always knew what I wanted to write.
